    {
      "id": "de668cb4b4acbbb91c0df80603ce703ade517ec9",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 676,
        "name": "Steve Guminski",
        "email": "stephenx.guminski@intel.com",
        "username": "sguminsx",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2016-12-05 18:04:30.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 4:\n\nsetup_obd_uuid() is called by both llapi_ostlist() and cb_getstripe(), and the latter accepts a DIR *pointer.  So if the parameter to setup_obd_uuid() is changed to a file descriptor, there are two options. 1 - Add a dirp() call to cb_getstripe(), or 2 - rewrite the callback functions to use file descriptors as I did in my patch.  Is approach 1 acceptable?",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 4
    },
    {
      "id": "af7fd7b7264f6969cd491c74bd6bec036fdbf6aa",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 177,
        "name": "John Hammond",
        "email": "jhammond@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "jhammond"
      },
      "date": "2016-12-05 18:12:24.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 4:\n\n> setup_obd_uuid() is called by both llapi_ostlist() and cb_getstripe(), and the latter accepts a DIR *pointer.  So if the parameter to setup_obd_uuid() is changed to a file descriptor, there are two options. 1 - Add a dirp() call to cb_getstripe(), or 2 - rewrite the callback functions to use file descriptors as I did in my patch.  Is approach 1 acceptable?\n\nHi Steve, yes approach 1 is what I had intended.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 4
    },
    {
      "id": "185dcec1fe91928490cd4c0baec4876aada4ff1d",
      "author": {
